{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_heron_ver02/data/sn89079026/00414189970/1938021001/0417.xml":{"full_text":"COULEE OITY DISPATCH\nI. W. (BOB) HILSON, Editor\nTelephone 382 and 3883\nBntered at the postoffice at Coulew\nCity, Wash,, as second-class matter,\nfublished Every Thursday Morning\nin the Interest nf Coulee City and\nthe Neighboring Vicinity.\nBUYING A BOOM\nBuy at home and your home will\nboom! il\nNow that the 1933 game of looking\nfor prosperity\u2019s corner lias given way\nto the 1938 pastime of waiting for\nthe upturn in business, it is well to\nremember that business reovery, likw\ncharity, begins at home.\nDespite industrial troubles, labor\nconflicts and international clouds on\nthe horizon, Dun and Bradsreet\u2019s Jan\nuary survey of retail trade in thus\nstate reveals that the public has agsin\nbegun to buy. This climb iz all the\nmore enocouraging because it began in\nthe post-Christmas period, a period\nS A\nPy A\nP P\no LN i\nR S\nTRADENG SRS 8 MARK\nBe considerate! Don\u2019t cough in the movies. Take along a box of\nSmith Brothers Cough Drops for quick relief. Black or Menthol\u2014s\u00a2.\nSmith\u00dfros. Cough Drops are the onlydrops containing VITAMIN A\nThis is the vitamin that raises the resistance of the mucous\nmembranes of the nose and throat to cold and cough infections.\nin SEATTLE\nOn Brd Avenue and Stewart Street\nby Bon Marche Dept. Store\nSI.OO PER DAY\u2014Single $1.50 PER DAY\u2014Double\n$4.00 PER WEEK-\u2014and up\nHot and Cold Water in Every Room Phone in Room\nSTEAM HEAT and FREE SHOWERS\nBATHS GOOD and CLEAN\n\u201424. Hour Sexvice\u2014\ni N i\nLB A\n=k\u00a7,,-\u2014-\u00bb M of Helpful Household Hints\n@\u00e9z\ufb02' and Recipes\nM *f\"\u2014J-;J Conducted by ELEANOR HOWE\nTo keep the\nfloors and\nfurniture from\nbeing covered\nwith dust af\nter taking care\nof a hot-air fur\nnace, try this\n{dea: Close all\ndampers on the pipes leadinz to dif\nferent rooms; then shake the fur\nnace, carry out the ashes, and put\nthe coal in. Finally, reopen the\ndampers after the task is finished.\n90 e\nTo cook bacon easily and per\n\u2018ectly, place a round cake rack in\n\u00a5our heavy skillet. Then place\nstrips of. bacon, on, the rack and\n<ook in a slow; oxen. The fat drains\n\u00abto the skillet and bacon cooked\nin this way. ig deliciously crisp,\ne o\nWhen one pre\npares long-cooking\nB A cereals the night\nG\\ before in a double\n\u2019Ea Sboller, a disagree-\nU able skin may form\nm,m on the surface be\nfore serving time\nA in the morning. To\navoid this, simply\n<eep the breakfast food covered\nwith 3% inch of water while it\nstands overnight. At breakfast\ntime, reheat the cereal, mix in the\n~\u00a5ater, and serve.\n9\nICE CREAM FREEZER ICE\nCREAM: (Makes 1 quart.) Frozen\nIn a modern agitator freezer, ice\ncream becomes a delictous, creamy,\nuffy dessert that is free from ice]\n\u2018rystals\u2014and' after only 6 to 10\nninutes of turning. Scald 1% cups\nf mi'k. Mix and blend 1 cup sugar, 1\ntablespoons. flour and 1, teaspoon\nalt; and mix to a smooth paste|'\nwith cup of cold milk, Add this|\nmixture to the scalded milk and\nook, stirring oonstantly, until\nhick, In a double boiler for 16 min-\nutes. Beat 2 egg yolks well and|\u00a2\ncombine them with the hot mix.\nture, stirring constantly, cooking 3\nminutes longer. Add 2 teaspoons of\nvanilla and chill. Whip 1 cup whip- f\u20ac\nping cream and fald it into the: ice\ncream. Pour mixture into the freez- b\ning container of modern ice cream\nfreezer. (To allow for expansion,\nfill contalner not more than |0\nfull.) Assemble amd cover. Then|f\npack mixture of cracked ice and|n\nl@ salt (uge S_Juru ice to\\ one\nThose dollars just sneaking out of\nhiding are potential units in commun-\nity purchasing power, bricks to build\nour local prosperity,\nMore and more, people are learn\ning to spend their dollars at home.\nOnce there was some excuse for shop\npers going out of town to make their\npurchases, Today you can buy any\nthing from pins to pianmos right here\nat home under service, price and sel\nection conditions unsurpassed in any\nother eity.\nPurchasing power is your weapon\nthe fight against business recession,\nWhere you enter the battle determines\nwhere your forece will be felt by the\nenemy, If conditions here in your\nhome community are important $o\nyou, then join battle to win the war\nright here at home, With dollars as\nbullets, send old man recession fly\ning out of town on a flood of buying,\nbuying that will build a boom.\nTo speed progress....to make your\ndollars do more work for yourself and\nyour neighbors....BUY AT HOME.\nIR\nCARTOON OLICKS\nFor omce we cheer the Spokesman-~\nb e L\ne|part salt by volume) around the\nd freezing containgr. Turn crank\nn|slowly but steadily. When mixture\nd| becomes too stiff to turn, remove\ncover carefully, take out dasher,\nef{and pack down evenly with spoon,\nn t Cover with wax paper, replace lid,\nsfand draw off water from ice and\n1} salt mixture. Replentsh ice and\n-]lsalt mixture and allow to ha.den\n-1 at least one hour before _serving.\nte s\ne Take 4 cups of\nlarge cranberries\nand to them add A\n2 cups brown sug-\n,|Br and 2 cups\ne ;'hite sugar. Add\ncup water\n(enough to cover g\ni bottom of pan)\nand simmer gent- e o\nly for about 3% hour. If cooked\nslowly in this way the cranberries\n\u201cfwill look like large cherries in\n3 fheavy syrup and make a very de-\nL sirable winter fruit sawce.\n3 B 9 8\nWhy not allow small portions ot\nleft-over boiled or bake:d potatoes\nto accumulate and then make them\n'lup into that all-time favorite\u2014\nHOT POTATO SALAD!! Here is a\nstandard recipe which can be ad\njusted or changed in accordance\nwith the contents of one's refriger\nator; it will servig six preople. Skin\n'land slice 6 medfium-sized cooked\npotatoes. Pan bripil 4 slices of ba\ncon, which have been minced, and\nthen saute one m jedium-sized onion,\nwhich has been sliced, in the drip\npings. Heat toge ther cup water,\ncup vinegar, 1 teaspoon sugar,\nteaspoon sall and 34 teaspoon\npepper and ther; mdd this mixture\nto the onion in t h e frying pan. Add\nbacon. Combine his mixture with\nthe potatoes and place in baking\ndish to heat in moderate oven\n(350\u00b0) before serwi ng.\nv\nSmall quantities of fruits, either\nfresh or canned, ame often left over\nafter a meal. Swo :h fruits may\nbe stored in a m 10dern aircom\ngditloned ice refrigerator to be cut\nfup later into small ieces and serv\n\u2018ed combined as a Fruit Cup for\n\u2018either a dessert, f) 4 1t cocktail, or\nbreakfast eye-opeme ir. Besides koep\ning such fruits pr opa'rly cold, the\nclean-washed, moi; gt a'ir in these\nmodern ice refrige rator.\u00ae helpz the\nfrults retain their origi'nal fresk\nness and flavor,\nOopyright 1938 t g @icens Memg,\nCOULEE OFfY DISPATOM THOUREDAY, PEBEVARY 70, 1548\nReview cartoonist, who, Monday,\npaused long enough from his preju\ndiced \u2018\u2018dige\u2019\u2019 at the administration\nto depict something that, for a change,\nreally hits home, The cartoon in ques\ntion depicts our good old Uncle Sam\nin the act of severely chastizing Jap\nanese fisherman caught infringing on\nour Alaskan fisheries,\nPerhaps if the Review would de\nvote more of its cartoon and editorial\nspace along these lines and less along\nthe futile and unjust lines this good\nold family paper has followed in the\npust-\u2014but whoa, let\u2019s not get started\non that. The fact remains that for\nonce; their cartoonist has got some\nthing there, and may we be the first\nto congratulate him,\nSUPER-GIANT\nAnother momentous milestone in\nthe history of man\u2019s exploration of\nthe vast interstellar spaces has beem\nachieved,\nDr. Otto Struve and his two as\nsociates at Yerkes Observatory, \u2018Wil\nliams Bay, Wieconsin, are responstble\nfor one of the most outstanding ev\n\u2018ents in twentieth cemtury through\nitheir discovery a few days ago of the\nlargest star yet found in the umiverse,\nThis monster-sized super-giant of\nthe skypaths makes Old Sol look like\na B-B shot, Its radius is three thous\nand times that of the sun, or about\n2000 millions miles. However, this\nstellar leviathan is a dull red amber\nin comparison with the sum, whose\ntemperature is more than five times\ngreater, v.@_;g\nTo the explorers who tracked dowsm\nthis super-giant of all stars, its size\nis much the less important part of the\ndiscovery. The other part is that the\nunderside of this sky monstter is eov\nered with a blanket of gas known &S\nthe Heaviside layer. It\u2019s this layer,\nsheathing Mother Earth, that makes\nradio broadcasting possible. Without\nit, there\u2019d be ne programs of .Amos\n}\u2019n Andy, nor Jack Benny, nor Fred\nAllen, 2 4\nWith the exception of our earth,\nthis Heaviside layer has never before\nbeen found on any other heavenly\nbody. e\nMan\u2019s increasing knowledge of the\ninfinite zones of the heaven may make\nearth seem like a particle of dust\nfloating in space, but these discover\ntles remind us that history isn\u2019t made\noy statesmen and generals alone,\nHartline Briefs\nMr. and M. Tom Higginbotham\nR rs, McCann of Coulee. and Geo.\nHni\ufb02botham were called to Tacoma\nby the death of thgir aunt, Mrs, Neb\n[tie Coon,\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Frank have re:\nturned from their honeymoon and\nhave taken up residenmge in Grand\nCoulee,\nMartin Oien was called to Spokane\nSaturdey night b the serious illness\nof his sister, Mrs, Walter Dixomn,\nMr, and Mrs, Cole Elder were Spo\nkane shoppers Tuesday,\nMs, Chris Brown of Delrio is car\ning for her mother, Mrs, Ole Flet\nten, who is convalescing from an at\ntack of inffiuenza.\nMiss Verwn Schrook is in Spokane\nhospital reaeiving treatments,\nRev. H, V. Guerney has been car\nrying the mail the past week,\nThe Ladies Aid met at the home of\nMrs, George Higginbotham Thursday\nwith eight members and five visitors\npresent, A delicious lunch was gserved\nby the hostess, Mrs, Joe Kendall fur\nnished tea tpowels to work om,\nRolast goose with afl the fixin\u2019s\nwas served by Mrs. L, L. Frederich\nSaturday ewening in honor of her\nhusband\u2019s \u20183lst birthday. Guests in\ncluded Mr. and Mrs, A. J. Frederich,\nMiss Dorotthy: Patton, Miss Florence\nMcDoneld, Nliss Darrell Attebury,\nand V., O. Afttebury\u2019,\nE. I. Evans has boen in Olympia\nthe past weelt on offici\\l business\nKISS AND MAKE \\\\P?\nFEV husbands can understana?\nwhy a wife should turn from\npleasant companion into a shrew\nfor one whole week in every month.\nYou can say \u201cI'm sorry\u2019 and\nkiss and !;l:ke up Bea:\u2019or l}gfore\nmarriage t| after. Be wise. Ifyou\nwant to hold your husband, you\nwon't be a three-quarrter wife.\nFor three generatio nsone woman 7\nhas told another hovs to go *\u2018smile i\ning through\u2019 with L.ydia E. Pink- il\nham's Vegetable Compound, Is i\nhelps Nature tone \u2018up the system,\nthus lessening the a 1 scomforts from I\nthe functional disorders which\nwomen must endure in the three\nordeals of life: 1, Turning from\ngirlhood to womsnhood. 2. Pre\nparing for mothixhood. 3. Ape\nproaching \u201c\u2018middle age.\u201d 1\nDon't be a thr ee-quarter wifo,\nPERs Soartsbie\nVEGET.\nGogsn\ufb02lu Thooyugh\"\nRaymond Rutter is driving a\nChevrolet, recently purchased from\nH. H, Higgins,\nJules Feryn of Almira purchased\nteam of horses from A, J. Frederich\nthis woeek.\nOle Fletten drove to Coeur d\u2019Alene\nSaturdey to visit his daughter, Mil\ndred. He returned Sunday.\nMr, and Mrs. Frank Wasoba and\nMrs. Joe Kendall were Almira visit\nors Friday.\nBorn to Rev, and Mrs, H. V. Guer\nney Monday moraing, February 7. a\ndaughter,\nThose reported on the sick list the\npast week are Mr, and Mrs. Jas. Un\nderwood, Donald Underwood, Mrs, D,\nH, Jolly, Mrs. E. I. Evans, Mrs. Ole\nFletten, Mrs, Alva Higginbotham,\nPaul Walters, Mr. Allison, Miss Treca\nKelley, Rose Marie Higgins, Eva\nCarey. Earl Pease Br. and Earl Pease\nJe.\nBe Prepared For Spring Work\nWith\nJ. L CAS